const faqItems = [
	{
		question: 'What is the best custody schedule for a 7-year-old?',
		answer:
			'For many 7-year-olds, the best custody schedule is one that protects school stability while giving meaningful time with both parents. A 2-2-5-5 schedule or 5-2-2-5 schedule is often a strong starting point because each parent can handle predictable school nights and weekends still alternate. Some families can use week-on/week-off if the child is organized, both homes support school routines, and the child handles longer blocks well. A 60/40 schedule may be better when one home anchors more school mornings or activities. The right choice depends on distance, homework systems, transportation, extracurriculars, and the child\'s ability to stay organized. Use the Custody Schedule Generator to preview real dates, then test whether homework folders, activity equipment, reading logs, and transportation would actually work.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Is 50/50 custody a good schedule for a 7-year-old?',
		answer:
			'50/50 custody can work well for a 7-year-old when parents live near school, communicate about homework, and can both manage school-night routines. At this age, equal time needs more than enough beds and clothes in each home. It needs backpacks, reading logs, activity equipment, school portals, project deadlines, library books, and transportation to move smoothly. A 2-2-5-5 or 5-2-2-5 plan often works better than a highly fragmented equal-time schedule because weekdays stay predictable. If equal time creates late homework, forgotten supplies, repeated lateness, or activity conflicts, a 60/40 or modified plan may be more practical. Before choosing 50/50, compare the calendar with a custody percentage calculator and ask whether both homes can handle ordinary school responsibilities, not just overnights.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What custody schedule works best during the school year?',
		answer:
			'During the school year, many 7-year-olds do best with a schedule that makes weekdays easy to predict. 2-2-5-5 and 5-2-2-5 schedules can work because parents know which school nights they usually handle. Week-on/week-off can work for organized children and cooperative parents, but it may create long stretches away from one parent and requires strong homework systems in both homes. A 60/40 schedule may fit when one parent handles more school transportation or activities. The best school-year schedule should answer practical questions: who checks homework, who signs reading logs, who stores sports gear, and how school notices get shared. Many families use a different summer or holiday schedule, so the school-year plan should not be forced to solve vacations too.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Is week-on/week-off custody good for a 7-year-old?',
		answer:
			'Week-on/week-off can be good for some 7-year-olds, but it is not the best first choice for every family. The benefit is simplicity: fewer exchanges, fewer backpack handoffs, and a full week for homework and activities in one home. The challenge is that a full week can feel long if the child misses the other parent, has anxiety around transitions, or needs more frequent contact. It also requires both homes to be fully prepared for school mornings, projects, activities, and transportation. Families considering week-on/week-off should compare it with 2-2-5-5 and 5-2-2-5 before deciding. It usually works best when parents live close enough to school, both homes track assignments well, and the child does not feel disconnected during the full-week block.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How do sports and extracurricular activities affect custody schedules?',
		answer:
			'Sports and activities can quickly expose whether a custody schedule works in real life. A 7-year-old may have soccer practice, baseball games, dance, music lessons, martial arts, tutoring, or birthday parties. Parents need a plan for who drives, who pays, where equipment is stored, and whether both parents can attend events. A schedule that looks fair on paper may fail if cleats, uniforms, instruments, or homework folders are always at the wrong house. The parenting plan should identify transportation responsibilities, communication expectations, and how conflicts between custody time and activities will be handled. For activity-heavy children, 5-2-2-5 or a customized schedule may reduce midweek confusion because each parent has longer blocks to manage practice nights.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Should homework stay in one house or both homes?',
		answer:
			'Homework usually needs a system in both homes, even if one parent handles more school nights. A 7-year-old may have reading logs, spelling practice, math worksheets, school projects, library books, or online assignments. Keeping all homework in one house can reduce lost papers, but it can also make the other home less connected to school. Many families use a shared folder, school portal access for both parents, duplicate supplies, and a rule that the backpack travels with the child. The goal is not to make each home identical. The goal is to make homework predictable no matter where the child sleeps. If homework repeatedly goes missing, the custody schedule may need fewer school-night exchanges or clearer responsibility rules in a parenting plan template.',
	},
	{
		question: 'How do I create a custody schedule for a 7-year-old?',
		answer:
			'Start with the school week, not the weekend. Identify school start time, pickup time, homework expectations, activity days, transportation distance, and which parent can reliably handle mornings. Then compare common patterns such as 2-2-5-5, 5-2-2-5, week-on/week-off, and 60/40. Use a custody schedule generator to preview the calendar with real dates, then check whether backpacks, homework, sports gear, and parent-teacher communication will work. A good 7-year-old schedule should be easy enough for the child to understand and detailed enough that parents know who is responsible for school items, activities, and holiday changes. After choosing the weekly rhythm, put the details into a custody schedule template or parenting plan template.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Is there a custody schedule template for a 7-year-old?',
		answer:
			'Yes. A custody schedule template for a 7-year-old should include regular weekly parenting time, exchange days, school transportation, homework responsibilities, activity transportation, holiday rules, summer changes, and communication expectations. A simple template is often better than a vague agreement because school-age children have more moving parts than preschoolers. The template should state who handles reading logs, school portals, backpacks, uniforms, equipment, sick days, and school breaks. You can start with a custody calendar template or custody schedule template, then add school-age details in a parenting plan template. The most useful template is specific enough that a parent knows what happens on a Thursday soccer practice night, not just who has the overnight.',
	},
	{
		question: 'Can siblings have different custody schedules?',
		answer:
			'Siblings can have different custody schedules, but the decision should be practical and child-centered. A toddler may need shorter separations, while a 7-year-old may need a schedule built around school, homework, friendships, and activities. A teenager may prefer longer blocks or more flexibility. Keeping siblings together can be emotionally helpful and easier for parents, but forcing every child into the same schedule can create problems when their needs are very different. Some families keep the same exchange days but adjust calls, activity transportation, or overnight blocks. The key is to avoid creating a calendar so complicated that no one can follow it.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What custody schedule works best if parents live far apart?',
		answer:
			'If parents live far apart, a frequent-exchange schedule may be hard for a 7-year-old because travel can interfere with homework, bedtime, activities, and school mornings. A 60/40 schedule, every other weekend plan with midweek contact, or custom arrangement may be more realistic than strict 50/50. The farther the homes are from school, the more important transportation planning becomes. Parents should decide who drives, how late exchanges can happen, how school supplies move, and whether the lower-time parent receives more holiday or summer time. Less equal does not always mean less thoughtful if it protects school stability. In long-drive situations, fewer exchanges may help the child arrive at school rested and prepared.',
	},
