			'A 6-year-old is usually adjusting to early elementary school, so the best schedule often looks similar to a 7-year-old schedule but with slightly more emphasis on routine and transition support. Many families compare 2-2-5-5, 5-2-2-5, or a modified 60/40 plan. The schedule should protect school mornings, reading practice, early homework, bedtime, and backpack organization. Some 6-year-olds can handle week-on/week-off, but others still need more frequent contact and shorter gaps between parents. If a dedicated 6-year-old guide is not available, use this page with extra attention to early-elementary routines and compare it with the 5-year-old custody schedule guide. The practical test is whether the child gets to school rested, brings the right folder, and knows which parent handles each school night.',
	},
	{
		question: 'What is the best custody schedule for an 8-year-old?',
		answer:
			'An 8-year-old may be ready for slightly longer blocks than a younger school-age child, especially if both homes are organized and close to school. 2-2-5-5 and 5-2-2-5 are still strong options, while week-on/week-off may become more realistic for some families. Activities, friendships, homework, and school projects often matter more at this stage. The best schedule should let the child participate in sports, birthday parties, school events, and homework routines without feeling like every transition disrupts the week. If a dedicated 8-year-old guide is not available, start with the same school-age principles on this page. Then adjust for maturity: an 8-year-old may track supplies better than a 7-year-old, but adults still need shared calendars, school portal access, and activity rules.',
