			'A 10-year-old often has stronger organization skills, more established friendships, more activities, and more opinions about the weekly routine. Many 10-year-olds can handle longer blocks better than a 7-year-old, so week-on/week-off may be more practical if both homes support school and activities. 2-2-5-5, 5-2-2-5, and 60/40 can still work well depending on travel and parent availability. The best plan should account for homework load, sports, sleepovers, clubs, and the child\'s ability to manage supplies between homes. If a dedicated 10-year-old guide is not available, use this page and lean toward older-child independence. Still, parents should avoid giving a child adult-level responsibility for coordinating calendars, rides, school projects, or schedule changes.',
