					<div class="grid gap-4">
						<p>
							At age 7, children are usually fully engaged in elementary school. They may be reading independently, bringing home assignments, joining sports, forming stronger friendships, and becoming more responsible for their own backpack, books, and routines.
						</p>
						<p>
							A custody schedule that works for a toddler may not work for a 7-year-old. The focus shifts from naps and separation length to school success, homework, activity transportation, friendships, and predictable weekday routines.
						</p>
						<p>
							The best custody schedule for a 7-year-old is the one that keeps the child connected to both parents while making school nights, homework, activities, and social life easier to manage.
						</p>
					</div>
					<div class="soft-card rounded-[1.5rem] p-5 text-sm leading-6">
						<p class="font-semibold text-primary">Educational note</p>
						<p class="mt-2 text-secondary">
							This guide is informational only and is not legal advice. Custody decisions should account for your child, existing orders, safety, school needs, and local guidance when needed.
						</p>
					</div>
